CICD-PROJECT Used Cars EDA

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

An automobile dealership in Los Vegas specializes in selling luxury and non-luxury vehicles. They cater to diverse customer preferences with varying vehicle specifications, such as mileage, engine capacity, and seating capacity. However, the dealership faces significant challenges in maintaining consistency and efficiency across its pricing strategy due to reliance on manual processes and disconnected systems. Pricing evaluations are prone to errors, updates are delayed, and scaling operations are difficult as demand grows. These inefficiencies impact revenue and customer trust. Recognizing the need for a reliable and scalable solution, the dealership is seeking to implement a unified system that ensures seamless integration of data-driven pricing decisions, adaptability to changing market conditions, and operational efficiency.

Objective¶

The dealership has hired you as an MLOps Engineer to design and implement an MLOps pipeline that automates the pricing workflow. This pipeline will encompass data cleaning, preprocessing, transformation, model building, training, evaluation, and registration with CI/CD capabilities to ensure continuous integration and delivery. Your role is to overcome challenges such as integrating disparate data sources, maintaining consistent model performance, and enabling scalable, automated updates to meet evolving business needs. The expected outcomes are a robust, automated system that improves pricing accuracy, operational efficiency, and scalability, driving increased profitability and customer satisfaction.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a Used Cars. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

Segment: Describes the category of the vehicle, indicating whether it is a luxury or non-luxury segment.

Kilometers_Driven: The total number of kilometers the vehicle has been driven.

Mileage: The fuel efficiency of the vehicle, measured in kilometers per liter (km/l).

Engine: The engine capacity of the vehicle, measured in cubic centimeters (cc).

Power: The power of the vehicle's engine, measured in brake horsepower (BHP).

Seats: The number of seats in the vehicle, can influence the vehicle's classification, usage, and pricing based on customer needs.

Price: The price of the vehicle, listed in lakhs (units of 100,000), represents the cost to the consumer for purchasing the vehicle.

Correlation among variables¶
In [31]:

plt.show()

Observations:

  • The heatmap shows that price is strongly positively correlated with both Power (~0.79) and Engine (~0.67), indicating that more powerful and larger-engine cars tend to be significantly more expensive.
  • Price is moderately negatively correlated with Mileage (~-0.47), suggesting that higher fuel efficiency is associated with lower prices, consistent with economical cars typically being cheaper than high-performance models.
  • Power and Engine are very highly correlated (~0.88), so including both as predictors may introduce multicollinearity in linear models and could require regularization or dimensionality reduction.
  • Seats shows only weak correlations with price and other features, implying seating capacity by itself is a relatively minor driver of price compared with engine size and power.
  • Kilometers_Driven has near-zero correlation with price and other variables in this sample, indicating odometer readings alone do not show a strong linear relationship with price, though non-linear or segmented effects may still exist.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business?¶

Key conclusions from the analysis¶

  1. Segment is the primary price separator

    • Luxury cars have a mean price more than 4 higher than nonluxury cars and consistently sit in a much higher price band across all plots.
    • Even at similar power levels, luxury vehicles command a clear price premium, so brand/segment captures value beyond specs alone (features, finish, brand perception).

  2. Power and engine size are the strongest technical drivers of price

    • Price has strong positive correlations with Power and Engine, and the scatterplots show price increasing steeply with power, especially in the luxury segment.
    • Engine and Power are highly collinear with each other, so they represent a single underlying performance factor that dominates technical pricing.

  3. Fuel efficiency trades off with performance and price

    • Mileage is moderately negatively correlated with both Power and price: higherpowered, more expensive cars tend to have worse mileage.
    • Most cars cluster around moderate mileage values, with a few very highefficiency or zeromileage points that behave like outliers or potential dataquality issues.

  4. Usage (kilometers driven) and seating capacity matter less linearly, but highlight niches

    • Kilometers_Driven shows weak linear correlation with price overall, but boxplots reveal highmileage outliers, especially among 78seater vehicles, suggesting heavyuse fleet/peoplemover niches.
    • Seats has only weak correlation with price; it mainly segments usage patterns (e.g., powerful 2seater sports cars vs higherseater SUVs with moderate power).

  5. Distributions are skewed with influential outliers

    • Price, power, engine size, and kilometers are all rightskewed with a small number of very high values; these points can strongly influence simple linear models.
    • Log transforms and robust models (treebased, regularized regressions) are appropriate to handle skew and reduce outlier leverage.

Business recommendations¶

  1. Design a segmentaware pricing model

    • Build separate or interactionaware models for luxury vs nonluxury vehicles so that the system learns different pricepowerengine relationships per segment.
    • Use Segment as a mandatory feature in the pricing API, and monitor segmentlevel error (e.g., MAPE by segment) in your MLOps dashboards.

  2. Base core pricing on a performanceefficiency tradeoff

    • Make Power/Engine the backbone of the price prediction, with Mileage acting as a moderating factor (higher power increases price; better mileage offsets operatingcost concerns).
    • Expose this logic to sales teams as explainable features (e.g., +X lakhs for each 50 BHP in this segment), improving trust in automated prices.

  3. Handle outliers and special vehicles with explicit business rules

    • Flag extreme values (very high price/power/engine, zero or extremely high mileage, unusually high kilometers for 78seat vehicles) as special inventory that requires manual review or separate pricing logic.
    • In the pipeline, implement datavalidation checks and automatic capping/winsorization so that rare outliers do not destabilize model training.

  4. Implement lifecycle and usageaware adjustments

    • Even though linear correlation is weak, use kilometer bands (e.g., <30k, 3060k, 60100k, >100k) to apply modest depreciation adjustments within the model or as postprocessing rules.
    • Track how error behaves across usage bands; if certain highmileage bands are systematically mispriced, introduce specific features or models for highusage inventory.

  5. Operationalize with strong MLOps and monitoring

    • Ingest data from all dealership systems into a single, versioned feature store so the model always trains and serves on consistent definitions of Segment, Power, Mileage, etc.
    • Monitor:
      • Data drift for key drivers (distribution of Segment, Power, Engine, Mileage).
      • Performance drift (price prediction error by segment, by power band, by mileage band).
      • Business KPIs (gross margin, daystosale) before and after deploying the model.

  6. Use the model to support dynamic and competitive pricing

    • Combine your internal model predictions with external market data (e.g., regional average prices for similar specs) to adjust list prices in near real time while preserving target margins.
    • Surface recommendations such as undervalued/overvalued vehicles and priority to discount lists to sales managers, turning the model into a daily decision tool rather than a onetime estimator.
